<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Is the resurrection of Jesus a NECESSARY part of the Christian witness?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Do you mean this as:<br>
<br>
1) The actuality of it happening - that is, did He need to do it.<br>
2) Assuming that He did, must we believe that He did.<br>
3) Assuming that He did and we beleive that He did, must we evagelize that message.<br>
<br>
Out of these three I will answer the following.<br>
<br>
1)  While I feel that Christ's sacrifice is what atoned for our sins, I think the resurrection is the final triumph over death.  In that regard, I'm pretty sure that it is necessary when considering point one, although I will admit that there may be room for debate here when one considers the power of God to handle salvation in whatever manner He wishes - that is, He could have created a salvation plan that did not require the resurrection.<br>
<br>
2)  If He did, yes we must beleive that He did.  Not to do so would be to deny part of His being.<br>
<br>
3)  Here I could say maybe not.  While it is a central point of the message, I feel that for the most part the message of Christ dying for our sins is the true focal point.  However, once we mention that He died for our sins the inevitable question of &quot;then what?&quot; usually comes up and the resurrection is talked about.<br>
<br>
Overall, I can only say that the resurrection IS something that happened.  While I accept that nothing is really beyond the power of God and that His plan of salvation for us <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>could</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> have been accomplished in a way that did not require the resurrection of Christ thereby making (from a metaphysical point of view) the resurrection unnecessary.  However, it IS a part of the gospel and I'm not quite sure that I am willing to play soteriological (I think I used that right) &quot;what if?&quot;.<br>
<br>
